I agree with Arthur and Joan, insofar as the importance of including a Vet in the discussion if one can find a Vet who's willing to share the pain.  I give the lecture on Vietnam in our Western Civ. course at the college where I teach - it is deeply laden with the pain (I am a VN Vet, 3rd batt./1st marines '68 - '69).  However, I think it's important not to &quot;demonize&quot; the politicians.  If you think about it, weren't their intentions honorable, too?  Once we got into it (against the advice of some in the military) and they found out it wasn't going to be &quot;easy&quot;, they were faced with an impossible dilemma - do they escalate to the point required to &quot;win&quot; (I don't know what that point would've been) and risk a total war with China and the USSR, or do they get out and risk condemnation by many in the US?  Given those two options, they chose the middle course - try to hang on long enough to allow the SVN time to become capable of defending themselves.  I think the wisest choice would've been to get the hell out, but that's easy to say 30 years later.  Bottom line:  it's easy to condemn &quot;the politicians&quot; (they're easy targets - nobody likes 'em), but we're the ones who elect those people.  We're all responsible.
